{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_hobson_ver01/data/sn86075250/00517178974/1930110701/0357.xml":{"full_text":"A\nConstructive\nNewspaper\nTWENTY-SEVENTH YEAR\nBEET YIELD REACHES\n40,000 TON MARK;\nCAMPAIGN ENDING\nThe Harlem beet dump closed Wed\nnesday and it is expected that all beets\nin the valley will be on their way to\nthe factory by the end of this week.\nThe Sadler dump is the only one still\nrunning, Adams, North Fork and Malta\ndumps having closed early this week.\nThe beet yields are running above\nthe estimations made early in the sea\nson and the fair weather has made it\npossible to harvest every beet this\nyear. Threatening weather and an\nearly freeze put fear into tho hearts of\nthe entire valley about three weeks\nago with less than a third of the crop\non the way to market, but conditions\nduring the past two weeks were far\nmore favorable than average. Some\nshrinkage was caused by the freeze,\nbut despite that the tonnage will ex\nceed the 40,000 mark. The tonnage\nshipped from Harlem neared 4000. The\nbeets that remained in the ground until\nthe frost went out of them show little\neffects of the freeze.\nThe beet harvest should be com\npleted by Nov. 15 and the plowing of\nthe fields this fall is being strongly ad\nvocated. Sheep and cattle have been\nturned into many of the lots and are\nfeeding on the beet tops.\nCity Health Department\nSubmits October Report\nDr. W. N. Deatherage submits the\nfollowing report of the activities of the\ncity board of health for October:\nThe Board of Health of the city of\nHarelm met October 29, 1930, Mrs. Mae\nJones, Mrs. Georgia T. Tout and Dr.\nW. N. Deatherage present, the follow\ning proceedings were had to wit:\nMrs. Georgia T. Tout was appointed\nby the mayor of Harlem as a member\nof the board of health to fill the va\ncancy caused by the resignation of Mrs.\nGertrude Carnegie.\nThe condition of the city water was\ndiscussed, and as there has been so\nmuch complaint of the city water tast\ning and smelling like sugar beets, by\nthe users of said water, it was voted\nto take the matter up with the Sugar\nBeet Factory at Chinook and the State\nBoard of Health, regarding the water\ncondition and see if the matter can be\ncorrected. The October analysis re\nported Harlem city water okeh.\nThere being so much typhoid fever\nreported from sections up the river\nfrom us, and the water being so low\nin the river, it is decided that a re\nquest be made that we have analysis\nof the city water made at least every\ntwo weeks or oftener until the river is\nfilled with a larger flow of water.\nThe secretary made his report of the\ninspection of the food establishments\ndoing business in Harlem, the same be\ning in very good sanitary condition and\nall duly licensed by the state, save <^ne\ncase, and they are ordered to obtain\nlicenses at once.\nThe secretary read the report of the\nschool nurse of the Harlem schools as\nfollows: \u2018\u2018There has been 428 pupils\nexamined and out of that number there\nare 198 who have one or more defects;\n101 with defective teeth; 79 with nose\nand throat defects; 10 with heart and\nlung lesions, 7 out of the ten are In\ndians.\u201d\nNo deaths and three births reported\nsince our last meeting.\nFarm Work Rushed, As\nWeather Continues Fair\nThe weather for the week ending\nSaturday, Nov. 1, 1930, according to\nthe weekly report of Frank A. Math,\nmeteorologist of the weather bureau\nat Havre, was mostly fair and\npleasant during daylight hours with\ncool frosty nights. The last of farm\nwork is being pushed rapidly.\nThere was an average excess in tem\nperature of 4.4 degrees as compared\nwith normal. The highest temperature\nfor the week was 64 degrees on Fri\nday the 31st and the lowest was 22\ndegrees on Oct. 30. making the abso\nlute weekly range 42 degrees.\nThe highest temperature for the\ncorresponding period taken from 50\nyears of record was 79 on Oct 27, 1891\nand the lowest for the same period was\n5 below on Oct. 28, 1895.\nThe total precipitation for the week\nwas .11 inches.\nThere were four clear days, one\ncloudy day and two partly cloudy\ndays. The duration of registered sun\nshine was 55.9 out of the 70.2 hours\nthe sun was above the horizon making\n80 percent of possible sunshine.\nThe sun rose at the end of the\nweek at 7:07 a.m. and set at 4:59 p.m.,\nmaking the length of day 9 hours\nanti 52 minutes.\nThe wind force was gentle to strong\nwith the prevailing direction from\nthe southwest. The highest velocity\nwas 31 miles per hour from southwest\non the 26th.\nHarlem Youth Wounded\nSunday in Hunt Accident\nWord from the Sacred Heart hospital\nat Havre states that Ray Nullinger of\nthis community is a patient there suf\nfering from wounds received while out\nhunting Sunday. No particulars are\navailable beyond the facts that young\nNullinger is suffering from a bullet\nwound in his left leg, just below the\nknee.\nAn operation was performed to re\nmove the bullet which had lodged in\nthe leg, resting against the ankle bone.\nTHE HARLEM NEWS'\nPUBLISHED IN THE HEART OF THE FAMOUS MILK RIVER VALLEY,\nMOODY\u2014MATHESON\nMiss Myrtle Moody, teacher for the\npast year at the Fort Belknap Board\ning School, became the bride Friday of\nMurdock Matheson, prominent Blaine\ncounty rancher of the North Fork dis\ntrict. The marriage took place at the\nGrand Hotel at Havre, Friday evening,\nthe Rev. R. M. Bickle, officiating.\nTracy Crook of this city and Miss\nDonna Farnsworth of Havre, attended\nthe bridal couple.\nAfter the ceremony, a wedding din\nner was partaken of at the Morris Case\nof Havre, after which Mr. and Mrs.\nMatheson departed by car for Great\nFalls to spend their honeymoon. They\nwill reside on the groom\u2019s ranch in\nthis county.\nWHAT THE REST OF\nTHE WORLD IS DOING\nRuth Hanna McCormick was defeated\nfor senatorial seat from Illinois by her\nDemocratic opponent, James Hamilton\nLewis by a vast majority, in Tuesday\u2019s\nelection. Franklin D. Roosevelt, gov\nernor of New York, was early conceded\nas returned to his office. Dwight W.\nMorrow led in the New Jersey sena\ntorial race. The wet and dry issue\nseemed to have little real effect, as\nthe winners were about equally divided\nin senatorial elections. Illinois, Rhode\nIsland and Massachusetts voted strong\nfor repeal of prohibition.\nSinclair Lewis, noted American auth\nor, native of the state of Minnesota,\nauthor of \u2018\u2018Main Street\u201d and many\nother novels, was awarded the Nobel\nprize for the best literature of 1930.\nLewis refused the Pulitzer award in\n1926 when his book, \u2018\u2018Arrowsmith\u201d\nwon him the recognition, but states he\nwill accept the Nobel prize, which\namounts to $46,350.\nArthur Bruce, Memphis, Tenn., resi\ndent and republican nominee for gov\nernor, was denied the right to cast his\nvote Tuesday when an election judge\nheld that Bruce had paid his poll taxes\ntoo late. The state law requires that\npoll taxes should be paid 60 days prior\nto election. Mr. Bruce left the polls\nwithout commenting.\nThree members of the Byrd expedi\ntion party received honors from the\nnavy department, Wednesday. Capt.\nAlton N. Parker, Los Angeles marine\ncorps officer, was given the distin\nguished flying cross for achievement\nas a test pilot; Victor H. Czegho of\nMassachusetts received the navy cross\nfor service as a machinist for the expe\ndition and Kannard Bubier of Wash\nington, D. C., was awarded the navy\ncross for service as an aviation me\nchanic.\nWilliam H. Thompson, mayor of\nChicago, was suddenly stricken ill with\nappendicitis and rushed to a hospital\nfor operation Friday. Latest reports\nstate that he is out of danger.\nThp huge Dornier flying boat Do-X,\nleft Altonrhein, Switzerland, Wednes\nday morning on the first leg of its pro\njected flight to New York City. The\nDo-X is a 12 motored sea plane. Three\nAtlantic stops, enroute, are planned,\none at Horta, an island of the Azores,\nanother at a fuel ship midway to Ber\nmuda and another at Bermuda.\n\u201cMontana in Rotogravure\u201d\nto be Printed in November\nSupport over the state for the pro\njected Montana advertising booklet,\n\u2018\u2018Montana in Rotogravure\u201d, has been\nso general that the promoters are ex\npecting to get the material to the\nprinters very shortly for production\nduring November, with the idea of its\ndistribution during the latter part of\nNovember and in December.\nAccording to information obtained\nby the state division of publicity, the\nstate has been covered from east to\nwest and north to south along the\nlines of the main railroads and the\ntourist highways with the result that\nnearly every city and the principal\ncommunity has co-operated through\ncontributions from commercial clubs\nand community organizations, indus\ntries and recreational agencies.\nThe booklets will carry hundreds of\ncuts reproduced from beautiful photo\ngraphs of Montana scenery, recrea\ntional sections, wild life, industries,\nApproximately 100,000 copies will be\nprinted and the booklet will be dis\ntributed through th> railroads, travel\nbureaus, commercial clubs and con\ntributing individuals and concerns\nthroughout Montana and other states\nof the union. Between 12,500 and\n15,000 copies will be placed with the\nstate division of publicity for its uses.\nInquiries for the booklet have\nalready been received by the producers\nin large numbers from California,\nFlorida, Illinois, Kansas and other\nstates.\nValue of Wheat for Feed\nShown by Comparison\nThe value of wheat for stock feed\nis shown by comparing the prices of\neach, the dates being October 1914 and\nOctober 1930.\nIn 1914 wheat was selling at $1.07 7-8\nper bushel, corn at 73 cents, and bran\nat $17.90 per hundred. Beef steers at\nthe same period were selling at 7%\ncents and lambs at 7 1-5 cents.\nIn October 1930, wheat was 85 cents,\ncorn 85 cents and bran at $20.50, while\nbeef steers were selling at 9 3-4 cents\nand lambs at $7.65 per 100 pounds.\nThe prices quoted above in grain is\nin carload lots f. o. b. St. PauL\nHARLEM, BLAINE COUNTY, MONTANA, FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 7, 1930\nBirds on Uncle Sam\u2019s Pension Roll\npF 1 z/\nf\nThomas Ross, pigeon expert of the. U. S. Army, with two of the homing\npigeons that served in the World War, carrying messages for the Signal\non the ft had eye shot out. \"Spike,\u201d at the right\nyarned 52 messages across hostile territory. r\nRE ELECTED\nSENATOR THOS. J. WALSH\nHOOVER CALLS NATION TO OBSERVE\nARMISTICE DAY WITH GRATITUDE\nWashington, Nov. 4. \u2014President Hoover today\ncalled on America to observe Armistice Day with\ngratitude that the agencies of peace have been\nstrengthened and the nation\u2019s relations with other\ncountries \u201care firmly grounded in amity and\naccord.\u201d\nThe following proclamation was issued:\n\u201cWhereas the 11th day of November, 1918, is\nforever memorable as the day upon which ended the\nworld war, with its attendant sufferings and vast\nwastage of human life; and\n\u201cWhereas it is fitting that the anniversary of\nthis day should be commemorated by exercises which\nshall do honor to all those who served our country,\nand especially to the memory of those who died in\nits service, believing that their sacrifice was in the\ncause of peace, which we thereby arc solemnly bound\nto do all in our power to advance and secure; and\n\u201cWhereas by concurrent resolution of the sen\nate and the house of representatives in 1926, the\nPresident was requested to issue proclamation for\nthe observance of Armistice Day;\n\u201cNow, therfore, 1, Herbert Hoover, President\nof the United States of America, in pursuance of the\nsaid concurrent resolution do hereby order that the\nflag of the United States be displayed on all govern\nment buildings on November 11, 1930, and do invite\nthe people of the United States to observe the day\nin schools and churches and other suitable places,\nwith appropriate ceremonies, giving expression to\nour gratitude that this year past has seen the agen\ncies of peace sensibly strengthened and that our\nrelations with other peoples are firmly grounded in\namity and accord.\n\u201cIn witness whereof, I have hereunto set my\nhand and caused to be affixed the seal of the United\nStates.\n\u201cDone at the city of Washington, this fourth\nday of November, in the year of our Lord, 1930, and\nof the independence of the United States of America,\nthe 155th.\n\u201c(Signed) HERBERT HOOVER.\u201d\nGirl Scout Troop Being\nSponsored by Auxiliary\nThe Harlem unit of the American\nLegion Auxiliary has assumed the\n.sponsorship of a troop of Girl Scouts\nand organization plans are now under\nway. Miss Kreider of the Lincoln\nSchool faculty has accepted tihe posi\ntion of captain of the Girl Scouts and\nwill have tho assistance of other\nteachers as lieutenants as well as a\ncommunity committee made up of\nwomen belonging to the Legion\nAuxiliary.\n\u2022Two patrols will be organized as a\nnucleus for tho local troop, girls of ten\nyears of age and over being eligible\nto membership. Girl Scout work is\nrelated to the work of the Boy Scouts\nbut is carried under separate rules,\nregulations and management.\nLegion to Sponsor Dance\nand Carnival Coming Week\nHarlem Legionnaires are sponsoring\nan Armistice Day dance at tho local\nhall Tuesday night, Nov. 11, as one of\ntheir activities of the winter. They\nwill also hold a two days carnival on\nFriday and Saturday, Nov. 14 and 15,\nat. Legion Hall. The Legion carnival is\none of the big funfests of the year and\nthose in charge promise many new and\nnovel features this year.\nHarlem Lions Plan Business\nRevival, Confidence Week\nHarlem Lions met as usual Monday\nevening for dinner together. The\nmeeting was held at the Masonic hall,\nthe dinner being prepared by Mrs.\nRing of The Blue Parrot and served\nto the men at the hall. Ernest Sundin\nwas initiated into Lionism at the\nmeeting and several other Harlem\nbusiness men wore guests of the club.\nPlans were inaugurated for a busi\nness revival and confidence week, all\npresent responding enthusiastically to\nthe plans suggested. President Roy\nNiewoehner, appointed commit tees and\ndefinite plans will be presented at\nnext Monday\u2019s meeting of the club.\nNEWS OF INTERESTING\nSTATE HAPPENINGS\nThe championship of the North Cen\ntral Montana district for Class B\nhonors in football will be settled Fri\nday at Chinook when the Chinook and\nChoteau teams will meet to decide\nwhich team is eligible to enter tho\nsemi-finals in the state championship\neliminations. Chouteau holds the oham\npionship in the Judith Basin division\nand Chinook in the Hi-Line district.\nBoth teams have only one loss in the\nseason\u2019s games, and in both cases it\nhas been to the Great Falls team.\nLieut. Governor Frank Hazelbaker of\nDillon has won a trip to Europe with all\nexpenses paid as a reward for his in\nsurance sales ability. The reward was\nmade to the salesman of each district\nwho showed the largest increase in\nsales during tho year and the lieuten\nant governor lead in the northwestern\ndistrict. He has left for Boston and\nwill sail for London, Saturday. While\nin Europe he will visit England, France,\nBelgium and Germany.\nF. Fred Williams of Havre died Wed\nnesday from the results of an explosion\nat the Wingfield ranch in tho Bearpaws\nMonday. Williams was engaged at the\nranch in digging a well. Rock was en\ncountered at 80 feet and two charges\nof dynamite wore placed in the well\nSaturday, one fuse being used. Tho\nblast went off and it was believed\nboth charges exploded. When Mr. Wil\nliams went into tho well to work Mon\nday. his pick set off the second charge\nand he was thrown into a small entry\nway near the bottom of the well.\nPartly stunned, the man crawled to\nwithin 15 feet of the surface whore he\nwas met by J. D. Smith, tenant of the\nranch, who grasped his hand, but was\nunable to hold Williams when lie faint\n<\u2022<l and fell back into the well. Death\ncame from the results of the fall, as\nwell ns tho blast.\nCapt. John Moran, Great Falls\nSpanish-American war veteran, died\nTuesday as the voters of Cascade coun\nty returned him to his office of county\nclerk and recorder for the ninth con\nsecutive term. Although Moran had\nbeen ill several weeks, his death came\nunexpectedly.\nMrs. Frank Metzel, widow of tho\nJefferson county sheriff who was ac\ncidentally shot in the hunt for the Har\nrison bank robbers, was appointed suc\ncessor to her husband to Herve until the\nfir\u00dft of the year.\nBetter Train Service for\nNorthern Montana Towns\nAll towns through northern Montana\nare rejoicing over the change in the\nGreat Northern train schedule as an\nnounced this week. Starting Sunday,\nNov. 9, the Oriental Limited train, No.\n4, will arrive in Harlem during the late\nafternoon at about 5 p. m., at practic\nally the same time it arrived here for\nmerly.\nFor over a year, northern Montana\nhas had no daylight passenger train\nservice with the exception of the local\ntrains. The change in schedule is very\ngratifying to the entire section.\nAnother change that will effect\ntravelers from here, also, is that of the\nGreat Falls train which will arrive in\nHavre at noon in order to connect with\nNo. 4, which leaves Havre at 3:35 p. m.\nOther slight changes in train time will\nbe noted in the train time table, but\nthese two are the only ones of much\nconsequence to Harlem residents.\nCONNECTED?\n\"Henry Morgan bought a second\nhand car yesterday.\"\n\"Henry Morgan went to Des Moines\nyesterday to have his eyes examined.\"\n(Consecutive items from The Geneva\nNews-Tribune.) \u2014Staley Journal\nJudge, severely, to cringing prisoner\n\u2014Now tell me, why did you steal that\npursei\nC. P.\u2014Yer Honor, I won\u2019t deceive\nyou. I was not feeling well, and I\nthought the change might do me good.\n\u2014Clipped\nDr. Slicem \u2014How is young Mr.\nSchmidt doing since his tonsil opera\ntion 1\nNice Nurse \u2014As affectionately as can\nbe expected.\nLyon\u2014What! That little insignifi-\ncant cur a police dogl\nBaer\u2014Why, yes. He doesn\u2019t look\nlike it, but that\u2019s because he\u2019s in the\nsecret service.\nNOTICE TO THE PUBLIC\nEveryone is urged to attend the\nmeeting of the Red Cross at the Ma\nsonic Hall, Monday night, Nov. 17 at\n7:30. The meeting will convene prompt\nly at the conclusion of the Lions din\nner.\nA\nConstructive i\nNewspaper\nNUMBER 46\nBLAINE VOTERS FOLLOW\nNATION-WIDE TREND\nFOVORING DEMOCRATS\nNearly 400 Harlem precinct voters\nwent to the polls Tuesday to cast their\nballots, showing an unusually strong\ninterest in the business of selecting\nofficials for the county and the. state.\nNationwide attention was turned to\nMontana\u2019s choice of her senator and\nshortly after the returns began coming\nin it was a certainty that the people of\nthe Treasure State had given to Sena\ntor Thomas J Walsh a huge majority\nand returned him to the U. S. Senate\nfor the fourth time. His victory nt\nthe polls Tuesday over Albert Galon\nwas one \u00bb>f the greatest of his career, it\nbeing certain that his votes would pass\nthe 100,000 mark. In Blaine county\nthe senatorial vote was Walsh\u2014l\u00df77;\nGalon\u201477o.\nNo change was made in Montane\nrepresentation nt Congress, Evans of\nthe first district winning easily over\nFitzgarrald, while in our own district\nScott Leavitt was given tho race of his\nlife by Tom Stout. Leavitt was con\nceded the election by Wednesday eve\nning with a brad of some 6000 votes.\nTho Blaine county vote was Stout\n-1230; Leavitt\u2014l376.\nLatest tabulations in the state give\nAssociate Justice Matthews a load of\nonly 134 over his Republican opponent,\nAlbert Anderson. With 174 precincts\nstill to hear from, tho results remain\nin doubt. Blaine county votes how\never accorded Justice Matthews a nice\nmajority, giving him 1367 votes to 959\nfor Anderson.\nRe-election of Leonard C. Young as\nrailroad commissioner was conceded by\nWednesday evening, although in Blaine\ncounty the voters showed a preference\nfor his Democratic rival by casting C 97\nvotes for Carey and 933 for Young.\nParty lines were broken in the coun\nty election, voters turning in mixed\ntickets in general. The closest contest\nwas that for county attorney, the re\nsult being uncertain to the hist minute\nwhen Harry L. Burns nosed out his\nDemocrat opponent, D. J. Sias, by 9\nvotes. Burns received 1326 votes?\nBias received 1317. Another close con\ntest was that for county commissioner,\nthe result being a victory for R. B.\nGannaway, Democrat, over Al Ekegren,\nRepublican. Totals were Gannaway\u2014\n-1311; Ekegren\u2014l292.\nG. W. Fleming was returned as sher\niff of Blaine county by a nice major\nity. Buckley, running as an Indepen\ndent cut down the vote of Baines, Re\npublican. giving Fleming an easy vic\ntory. Buckley drew a large vote in\nTTarlem, his own community. Totals\nfor sheriff were Fleming\u2014lls\u00df; Baines\n\u2014883; Buckley\u20147l\u00df.\nMiss Daisy I. Blackstone was named\ncounty superintendent by a wide mar\ngin over the present superintendent, G.\nH. Willman. Miss Blackstone polled a\nvote of 1536; Willman\u2014lls7.\nStineburg walked away with the\ncounty treasurer\u2019s position, receiving\n1578 votes to Fuller\u2019s 882. As public\nadministrator, Miller polled 1327 votes\nto Oveson\u2019s 629. Other county offices\nwere not contested, thus returning\nRoss and Ekegren to tho state assem\nbly as representatives from Blaine,\nChristensen as county assessor, Bauer\nas clerk and recorder, and Noyes as\nsurveyor.\nThe voters approved the two refer\nenda: a three mill tax for the Greater\nUniversity and a three million dollar\nbond issue for tho state institutions.\nIn Blaine county, as in tho nation,\nthe Democrats claim this election as a\nvictory. The extent of Democratic\nsentiment in this county came as a\nsurprise to many, as little open inter\nest was evident prior to election. The\nRepublican strongholds throughout the\ncountry were raided Tuesday, all indi\ncations pointing to a Democratic ma\njority in the House and a possible tie\nin the Senate.\nCorrect Windows Important\nin Saving Your Eyesight\nThe manner of admitting daylight\nto a room of a house or office is by\nno means a matter of indifference to\nthe inhabitants. It should always be\nremembered that the position of the\neyebrows, and the general structure\nand arrangement of the eyes and\ntheir appendages are chiefly to protect\nthem from light coming down from\nabove and thus they are defenseless\nagainst light which comes from below.\nOn this account low windows are\nto be avoided in favor of those higher\nup in the walls but if low windows are\nused they should be fitted with cur\ntains made to be drawn up rather than\ndown and the floors should be of dark\nmaterials which do not possess any\nstrongly reflecting surface. The cur\ntains too, should be of a suitable color,\nneither white or other light colors but\nof shades of brown, dark greens and\ntans, which are restful to the eye and\nthey should be of sufficient thickness\nto be really effectual for the purpose\nfor which they are designed.\nPersons who are called upon to use\ntheir eyes for fine work such as\nsewing, reading, or any similar pur\nsuits would do best to do this work\nduring the periods when daylight is at\nhand. Under artificial light nil eyes\nare prone to lose their acuteness of\nvision and their power of sustained\neffort.\nCounsel (in divorce case) \u2014I ask that\na recess be taken at this point, our\nHonor.\nJudge\u2014On what groundsl\nCounsel My client wishes to change\nher gown. She hasn\u2019t displayed half\nher costumes yet.","height":"23560","width":"17144"}}
